(1,$title$At the Galveston Dock$title$,$body$Liam noticed the problem before anyone said it aloud. In Galveston harbor in the 1850s, his family could not find their trunk among the crates. The room seemed to pause around a red ribbon tied to the handle, as if even ordinary things were waiting for a choice. A small worry tapped at Liam's thoughts, steady as rain on a window.

At first, Liam wanted the problem to belong to someone else. That would have been easier. But the longer Liam watched, the smaller that easy answer felt. So Liam took a breath and searched by remembering his mother's ribbon. The first try was awkward, and a few people looked over, but no one laughed. Instead, the silence loosened, and the problem began to look like something ordinary hands could fix.

By the end, the ribbon looked small, but it held their old life together. Liam walked away feeling lighter. The day had not become perfect, but it had turned, like a page, toward something kinder. Later, when Liam remembered the moment, the important part was not being brave right away. It was choosing to act while still feeling unsure.

